<li><a href="/wiki/Render_unto_Caesar" title="Render unto Caesar" class="mw-redirect">Render unto Caesar</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Self-ownership" title="Self-ownership">Self-ownership</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Thomas_Merton" title="Thomas Merton">Thomas Merton</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Weak_theology" title="Weak theology" class="mw-redirect">Weak theology</a></li>
<li>"<a href="/wiki/Fool_for_Christ" title="Fool for Christ" class="mw-redirect">Fool for Christ</a>": Christian <a href="/wiki/Asceticism" title="Asceticism">ascetic</a> and non-conformist tradition within <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Christianity" title="Eastern Christianity">Eastern Christianity</a>, see also "<a href="/wiki/Hermit" title="Hermit">Hermit</a>", and "<a href="/wiki/Stylite" title="Stylite" class="mw-redirect">Stylite</a>".</li>
<li><i><a href="/wiki/Jonathan_Livingston_Seagull" title="Jonathan Livingston Seagull">Jonathan Livingston Seagull</a></i></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Simone_Weil" title="Simone Weil">Simone Weil</a>: French philosopher, social activist, and Christian mystic of Jewish heritage; Weil died under forced exile in Britain during World War II at 34 years of age. Her major works, including "Oppression and Liberty", "Gravity and Grace", and "Waiting for God" were all published post-humously and to great acclaim. Since her death in 1944 her thought has steadily grown in influence. <a href="/wiki/Pope_Paul_VI" title="Pope Paul VI">Pope Paul VI</a>, a great proponent of <a href="/wiki/Catholic_Social_Teaching" title="Catholic Social Teaching" class="mw-redirect">Catholic Social Teaching</a>, counted Simon Weil as one of his major early influences.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/New_Monasticism" title="New Monasticism">New Monasticism</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Order_of_Watchers" title="Order of Watchers">Order of Watchers</a>: A French Protestant community of <a href="/wiki/Hermit" title="Hermit">Hermits</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/God:_Sole_Satisfier" title="God: Sole Satisfier" class="mw-redirect">God: Sole Satisfier</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Jan_Tyranowski" title="Jan Tyranowski">Jan Tyranowski</a>, solitary, mystic, and student in the teachings of <a href="/wiki/John_of_the_Cross" title="John of the Cross">John of the Cross</a>. He was a central figure in the spiritual formation of young Karol Wojtyla, who became pope <a href="/wiki/John_Paul_II" title="John Paul II" class="mw-redirect">John Paul II</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/The_Mormon_Worker" title="The Mormon Worker">The Mormon Worker</a></li>
</ul>
